All Dimensions required: Every qb:Observation has a value for each dimension declared in its associated qb:DataStructureDefinition.
In a qb:DataSet which does not use a Measure dimension then each individual qb:Observation must have a value for every declared measure.

If a dimension property has a qb:codeList, then the value of the dimension property on every qb:Observation must be in the code list. In the case of a skos:ConceptScheme then each concept must be linked to the scheme using skos:inScheme

If a dimension property has a qb:codeList, then the value of the dimension property on every qb:Observation must be in the code list.  In the case of a skos:Collection then the collection must link to each concept (or to nested collections) using skos:member. If the collection uses skos:memberList then the entailment of skos:member values defined by S36 in [SKOS-REFERENCE] must be materialized before this check is applied.

If a dimension property has a qb:HierarchicalCodeList with a non-blank qb:parentChildProperty then the value of that dimension property on every qb:Observation must be reachable from a root of the hierarchy using zero or more hops along the qb:parentChildProperty links.

If a dimension property has a qb:HierarchicalCodeList with an inverse qb:parentChildProperty then the value of that dimension property on every qb:Observation must be reachable from a root of the hierarchy using zero or more hops along the inverse qb:parentChildProperty links.
Every dimension with range skos:Concept must have a qb:codeList.
If a qb:DataSet D has a qb:slice S, and S has an qb:observation O, then the qb:dataSet corresponding to O must be D.
Every dimension declared in a qb:DataStructureDefinition must have a declared rdfs:range.
Every qb:DataStructureDefinition must include at least one declared measure.
Here you will find information about the DataCube information in the selected knowledgebase.
In a qb:DataSet which uses a Measure dimension then each qb:Observation must have a value for the measure corresponding to its given qb:measureType.
The only components of a qb:DataStructureDefinition that may be marked as optional, using qb:componentRequired are attributes.
Every qb:Observation has a value for each declared attribute that is marked as required.
Single Measure on Measure Dimension Observation
In a qb:DataSet which uses a Measure dimension then each qb:Observation must only have a value for one measure (by IC-15 this will be the measure corresponding to its qb:measureType).
Every qb:Slice must have a value for every dimension declared in its qb:sliceStructure.
Every qb:componentProperty on a qb:SliceKey must also be declared as a qb:component of the associated qb:DataStructureDefinition.
Every qb:SliceKey must be associated with a qb:DataStructureDefinition.
Every qb:Observation has exactly one associated qb:DataSet.
Every qb:DataSet has exactly one associated qb:DataStructureDefinition.
Each qb:Slice must have exactly one associated qb:sliceStructure.

In the following form, those dimension elements are listed that are used to express the context of the corresponding statistical observations. This is a multiple choice selection, which means that you are able to select a minimum of one and a maximum of all items. Please note that you have to select at least one item. If you select all items it can happen that the server has to respond with a very huge set of data which can can slow down the response and processing time.

The selected RDF dataset contains statistical context information of the observations. In a DataCube such contextual information are expressed as dimensions and dimension elements. To select observations of your interest you have to select elements belonging to these dimensions. The available dimensions are available in the box. Below every dimension the amount of selected and available dimension elements is diplayed. To change the slection please use the selection dialogue for each dimension.

In the following item list, the DataCube datasets available are part of the given dataset. These DataCube datasets are used to fragment the set of statistical data items. In order to visualize a chart using CubeViz, select one of the DataCube datasets below.

The selected RDF dataset contains a subdivision called “DataCube datasets” which are used to group different statistical data items. The structure of a DataCube dataset corresponds to a specific data structure definition. There may be cases where different DataCube datasets share their corresonding DataStructureDefinition. In the selection dialogue you have the option to change the selected DataCube dataset. If you do not select one of the subdivision, CubeViz will select one automatically.

Why are there different measurements and units?
Why are there different measurements and units?

Sometimes a dataset contains different measurement and units. This is the case where a statistical observation is being expressed for different purposes. For instance, a spatial distance between two things can be expressed using centimeter and meter. To improve the comparability of observations the user should determine both the measurement and the unit. Please use the selection dialogue to configure this according to your needs.
What is a dimension and why should I select elements belonging to a dimension?

Each data set contains statistical data. These data is a collection of so-called observations. Under an observation you can picture a point in a room. This point has coordinates which locates him at a specific position in this room. In general these coordinates are 3 dimensional: height, width and deep. In the DataCube context these coordinates are dimensions and it is possible to have more than these 3. But these dimension are not positions in a room, you may think, but could be everything, like a scala of money (e.g. from 1000 EUR to 100.000 EUR).
Why do i should use dataset filter?
A dataset filter set a fix amount of dimension elements. Its purpose is to give you a specific view of the data.

A dataset filter set a fix amount of dimension elements. Its purpose is to give you a specific view of the data. In general, the author of the data you see, use slices to show you remarkable observations or interesting facts.

No data fits to your selection, please adapt your selection in the left sidebar manually.

This behavior can have various reasons. On the one hand it is possible that there is no data available according to the selection. In order to reduce the load of the server we decided not to check the availability of data for every selection.

On the other hand it is possible that a chart can not be produced if the user selects inapplicable combinations of options such as a logarithm scale in combination with percentage stacking. Trapping such cases is not yet fully implemented but will be done soon.

To solve such problems we suggest to change the selection and/or the selected chart options.
